description.plain:
Dion Marquise Hayes (b. November 25, 1993), better known by the stage name 42 Dugg, is a Detroit artist who hails from the East Side. 42 (pronounced “four two”) found himself in trouble with the law early on in life, and by age 15 he was serving a six-year jail sentence. It was while incarcerated that he took up rapping, beginning to take it more seriously upon his release. He dropped his first song “Livin” on November 27, 2017.

From there, the rapper quickly ascended, self-releasing several projects like the 11241 Wayburn mixtape series. His early singles such as “The Streets” caught the attention of Yo Gotti, who signed 42 Dugg to his Collective Music Group label. A joint agreement allowed him to sign on with Lil Baby’s 4PF too.

After his feature spree, 42 Dugg returns with a new single, “Free Woo”. The song is dedicated to his locked-up friend Woo and he’s seen together with Dugg in the cover art.

The song marks Dugg’s second record dedicated to an incarcerated friend, after ‘'Free Merey’' which was released just before his feature run.

‘'Free Woo’‘ is the second single to Dugg’s mixtape, ‘'Free Dem Boyz’'.

42 Dugg dedicates the first single for his fourth mixtape Free Dem Boyz to Merey, an unknown friend of Dugg who is serving time.

The hip-hop record comes just after his huge feature on ‘'We Paid’' which debuted at #61 on the Billboard Hot 100 during the week of May 16, 2020.

description.plain:
“Still Catching Cases” marks 42 Dugg’s first attempt at drill which is a hip-hop style becoming more and more popular. To help him with this, Dugg enlists one of the biggest drill producers, 808Melo. Melo brings some adrenailne-fueled guitar 808’s along with a heavy bass, the perfect drill beat. Dugg also enlists Fivio Foreign and Rowdy Rebel, two big names in the drill scene.

The song marks the first collaboration between any of the artists.
